===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# {{lb|en|with {{m|en|on}}}} Originally, one's [[oath]] or word of honour, given as a condition of release from custody; now specifically, describing the [[release]] of a former [[prisoner]] under certain conditions, especially the promise of good behaviour. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|He will be on '''parole''' for nearly two more years.}}
#: {{ux|en|He was released on '''parole'''.}}
# Conditional [[release]] of a prisoner (now especially before the end of a custodial [[sentence]]), or the term or state of such release; the system governing such releases. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|The defendant shall be sentenced to life without the possibility of '''parole'''.}}
# {{lb|en|now|historical}} A word of honor, especially given by a [[prisoner of war]], to not engage in combat if released. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Macaulay History of England|passage=This man had forfeited his military '''parole'''.}}
#* '''1926''', {{w|T.E. Lawrence}}, ''Seven Pillars of Wisdom'', New York: Anchor (1991), p. 167:
#*: In hospital he gave his '''parole''', and was enlarged after paying for the torn blanket.
# {{lb|en|now|rare}} A [[watchword]] or code phrase; {{i|military}} a password given only to [[officer]]s, distinguished from the [[countersign]], which is given to all guards. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#* '''1791''', {{w|James Boswell}}, ''Life of Johnson'', Oxford 2008, p. 1143:
#*: ‘Classical quotation is the '''''parole''''' of literary men all over the world.’
# {{lb|en|linguistics}} Language in use, as opposed to language as a system. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
# {{lb|en|US|immigration law}} The permission for a foreigner who does not meet the technical requirements for a visa to be allowed to enter the U.S. on humanitarian grounds.
# {{lb|en|legal}} {{alternative form of|en|parol}}

